This paper discusses the use of indicators in research evaluation regarding internationalisation policies in higher education. The paper focuses on the policy context and how it affects the interpretation and policy implications of S&T indicators. The paper touches upon topics such as collaborations, language, and policy contexts, which are relevant to several sub-categories such as statistics (cs.ST), social and information networks (cs.SI), higher education (cs.HE), machine learning (cs.LG), and political science (cs.POLI).
